        <h2 id="what-is">What is Ubersuggest?</h2>
        <p>Ubersuggest is Neil Patel's all-in-one SEO toolkit. It started as a free keyword tool in 2017 (Neil bought it from Google search expert John Doherty) and has since grown into a paid platform covering keyword research, competitor analysis, site audits, backlink tracking, and rank monitoring.</p>

        <p>The core suite does five things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keyword Research</strong> — search volume, difficulty, related keywords, content ideas</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor Analysis</strong> — top pages, keywords, backlinks for any domain</li>
          <li><strong>Site Audit</strong> — technical SEO scan with prioritised recommendations</li>
          <li><strong>Backlinks</strong> — small but functional backlink database with new/lost tracking</li>
          <li><strong>Rank Tracking</strong> — daily position monitoring for tracked keywords</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Ubersuggest is <em>not</em>: a writing tool, a publishing platform, or an enterprise-grade dataset. It is a useful starter kit at a price point that no premium competitor matches.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Neil Patel acquired Ubersuggest in 2017 and rebuilt it as part of Neil Patel Digital. The tool runs on third-party data sources for the bulk of its index, which keeps costs low — and explains the data accuracy gap vs Ahrefs (own crawler, 8B pages/day). The lifetime deal is the company's main customer-acquisition lever.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Ubersuggest features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is surprisingly broad for the price. Here is what actually matters in daily use.</p>

        <h3>1. Keyword Research — the headline feature</h3>
        <p>Enter a seed keyword and Ubersuggest returns search volume, SEO difficulty (0–100), paid difficulty, CPC, related terms, and content ideas. The data is reasonable for high-volume head terms. For long-tail keywords under 200 monthly searches, accuracy drops sharply — we found Ubersuggest under-reporting volume by 30–60% compared to Ahrefs and Semrush on the same keywords.</p>

        <h3>2. Competitor Analysis</h3>
        <p>Drop a competitor's URL. Ubersuggest returns their top pages by traffic, top keywords, and backlink summary. Useful as a first-pass overview. Less useful for deep competitor research where you need historic position data, exact ranking pages, or the full backlink profile.</p>

        <h3>3. Site Audit</h3>
        <p>Crawls your site and surfaces SEO issues by priority. Catches the basics: missing meta descriptions, broken links, slow pages, missing alt text, thin content. Doesn't go as deep as Ahrefs Site Audit (100+ checks) or Semrush Site Audit (140+ checks), but covers what most small sites need.</p>

        <h3>4. Backlinks</h3>
        <p>Ubersuggest's backlink database is around 2 trillion links (Ahrefs has 35T+, Semrush 43T+). You see new and lost backlinks, anchor text breakdown, and referring domain authority. Functional for understanding your own backlink profile. Insufficient for serious competitor link analysis.</p>

        <h3>5. Rank Tracking</h3>
        <p>Daily position updates for keywords you add to projects. Tracks desktop and mobile separately, supports location targeting. The interface is clean. The data is accurate for the keywords it covers.</p>

        <h3>6. AI Writer (basic)</h3>
        <p>Ubersuggest added a basic AI writing tool in 2024. It generates short-form content (titles, intros, meta descriptions). The output quality is below ChatGPT or Claude. Not a replacement for writers.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">Ubersuggest pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>Ubersuggest's pricing is its biggest selling point. Most reviews quote the sticker. We'll quote the <em>full</em> cost — sticker plus everything you have to bolt on to actually publish content.</p>

